By the Law of Cosines on $\triangle APB,$ we find that
\[\cos \angle ABP = 1 - \frac{64}{50} = \frac{-7}{25}\]
This implies that
\[\sin \angle ABP = \pm \frac{24}{25}\]
We choose the positive root since the angle lies between $0$ and $\pi.$

By the Law of Sines on $\triangle APB,$ we find that
\[\frac{AP}{\sin \angle ABP} = \frac{AB}{\sin \angle APB}\]
Substituting yields
\begin{align*} AB &= 10 \cdot \frac{\sin \angle ABP}{AB} \\ &= 10 \cdot \frac{\frac{-7}{25}}{\boldsymbol{\left(}1 + \frac{64}{50}\boldsymbol{\right)}} \\ &= \frac{-14}{5} \cdot \frac{50}{39} \\ &= \frac{-28\sqrt{39}}{39}.\end{align*}
It follows that
\[\sin \angle PAC = -\frac{28\sqrt{39}}{50} = -\frac{14\sqrt{39}}{25}.\]
This implies that
\[\cos \angle PAC = \pm \frac{21\sqrt{39}}{50}.\]
We choose the positive root since the angle lies between $0$ and $\pi.$

By the Law of Sines on $\triangle PAC,$ we find that
\[\frac{AP}{\sin \angle PAC} = \frac{AC}{\sin \angle APC}\]
Substituting yields
\begin{align*} AC &= 10 \cdot \frac{\sin \angle PAC}{AC} \\ &= 10 \cdot \frac{\frac{21\sqrt{39}}{50}}{\boldsymbol{\left(}1 + \frac{28^2 \cdot 39}{50^2}\boldsymbol{\right)}} \\ &= \frac{210\sqrt{39}}{49\sqrt{13}} \\ &= \frac{30\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{13}}.\end{align*}
By Pythagorean Theorem on $\triangle ABC,$ we find that
\begin{align*} AC^2 &= AB^2 + BC^2 \\ \left(\frac{30\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{13}}\right)^2 &= \left(\frac{28\sqrt{39}}{39}\right)^2 + BC^2 \\ BC^2 &= \frac{900}{13} - \frac{784}{39} \\ BC &= \frac{56\sqrt{70}}{39}.\end{align*}
By the Law of Sines on $\triangle BCP,$ we find that
\[\frac{BP}{\sin \angle BPC} = \frac{BC}{\sin \angle BCP}\]
Substituting yields

\begin{align*} PC &= 6 \cdot \frac{\sin \angle BPC}{PC} \\ &= 6 \cdot \frac{\frac{56\sqrt{70}}{39}}{\boldsymbol{\left(}1 + \frac{56^2 \cdot 70}{39^2}\boldsymbol{\right)}} \\ &=\boxed{\frac{24}{\sqrt{5}}}.\end{align*}

