The area of $\triangle ADF$ is \[\frac{(AF)(AD)\left(\sin \angle FAD\right)}{2}.\]
We also know that  \[\frac{(AF)(AD)\left(\sin \angle FAD\right)}{2}=\frac{(AF)(AC)\left(\sin \angle FAC\right)}{2},\]so \[AD=AC \cdot \left(\frac{\sin \angle FAC}{\sin \angle FAD}\right).\]
Because $AD$ bisects $\angle BAC$, we know from the angle bisector theorem that \[\frac{AC}{AB} = \frac{FC}{BE} \Longrightarrow AC=AB\cdot \left(\frac{FC}{EB}\right)=12 \cdot 3=36,\] so \[AD=36\left(\frac{\sin 45^{\circ}}{\sin 135^{\circ}}\right)=\frac{36}{\sqrt{2}}=18\sqrt{2}.\]
The area of $\triangle ADF$ is now \[\frac{(AF)(AD)\left(\sin 45^{\circ}\right)}{2}=\frac{1}{2}\cdot10 \cdot 18\sqrt{2} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}=90,\] so the area of $\triangle DFC$ is $90 \cdot \frac{27}{10}=243.$
The area of quadrilateral $DCFG$ is twice the area of $\triangle DFC$, so the area of quadrilateral $DCFG$ is $2 \cdot 243=\boxed{486}$.

