By the Law of Cosines on $\triangle BAC
\[\sqrt{2006}=4a^2+4c^2-4ac\cos(\angle BAG)=41^2+4ac\cos\angle BAG.\]
Note that by the Law of Cosines on $\triangle BFD$,
\begin{align*} \sqrt{2006}&=4c^2+x^2-4cx\cos(\angle BFG)=41^2+4cx\cos\angle BFG \\
&=41^2+4(2006/82-x^2)c.
\end{align*}Setting the equations equal gives
\[4ac\cos\angle BAG=41^2-4\left(\frac{2006}{82}-x^2\right)c\quad (*)\]
and rearranging we get
\[c=\frac{41^2-4x^2}{153-4x^2}\cdot \frac{1}{\cos\angle BFG}.\]
Also we know that $c=a\cdot\sin (\angle BAG+\angle BFG)$ and
\[a=\frac{41^2-4x^2}{153-4x^2}\cdot \frac{1}{\sin\angle BFG}.\]
Then it is clear that $\sin\angle BAG=\cos\angle BFG = 1/\sqrt{2}$
Substitute this back into equation (*) and we get $41^2=2006+2x^2,$ so $x^2=625/8.$
Lastly, $[\mathcal{T}]=c^2=x^2+k^2,$ and since $k=\frac a{\sqrt2}=x/4\cdot\sqrt{82}=5\sqrt{82},$ thus $k^2=20500,$ and so $c^2=20500+390.625=\lfloor20500+390.625\rfloor+xxx,$ so we can see $20500\le c^2<21000$ so $K_{min}=20500$ is the only available integer and therefore the answer is 
\[\boxed{001}\].

