As medians of a triangle, $DE$ is in the ratio 2:1 from the midpoint of the median to the intersection of the medians, and from the intersection to the vertex ($D$ and $E$ to $P$ respectively). Thus $DP=\frac{2}{3}x$ and $EP=\frac{1}{3}x$, for $DE=x$. This gives the system of equations.
\begin{align*} DP + DE &=3 \Rightarrow \frac{2}{3}x + x=3 \Rightarrow x=1.5 \\ EP + DE &= 2 \Rightarrow \frac{1}{3}x + x= 2 \Rightarrow x=1.5 \ \ \ \ \ \ \checkmark \end{align*}
Subtract the two equations to obtain $DP - EP = 3 - 2 = 1$. Solving yields $DP=1.2$ and $EP=0.3$ (checking, this is a 5:12:13 triangle so we know we didn't make computational errors). The height of the trapezoid $AEDC$ is $DP + EP =1.5$. Because $DE$ is parallel to $AC$ and $AD$ is a median, $AC=2DE=3$. Thus, the area of $AEDC = \frac{(3 + 1.5) \cdot 1.5}{2}= \boxed{3.375}$ square units.

