The following system of equations can then be set up using the fact that the probability that the student chooses a particular lane at an intersection is $\frac{1}{2}$, as well as the conditions at the destinations:
\begin{align*} p_1(A) & = 1, \\ p_1(F) & = p_1(E), \\ p_1(E) & = p_1(D) + 2p_1(F), \\ p_1(D) & = p_1(H) + 2p_1(E), \\ p_1(H) & = p_1(G) + 2p_1(D), \\ p_1(G) & = p_1(C) + 2p_1(H), \\ p_1(C) & = p_1(B)+2p_1(G), \\ p_2(N) & = 1, \\ p_2(M) & = 0, \\ p_2(M') & = p_2(N) + 2p_2(L), \\ p_2(L) & = p_2(K) + 2p_2(M'), \\ p_2(K) & = p_2(J) + 2p_2(L), \\ p_2(J) & = p_2(I) + 2p_2(K), \\ p_2(I) & = 3p_2(J), \\ p_3(R) & = 1, \\ p_3(Q) & = 0, \\ p_3(P) & = p_3(O) + 2p_3(R), \\ p_3(O) & = 3p_3(P). \end{align*}
Solving this system gives $p_1(C) = \frac{49}{64},$ $p_2(I) = \frac{28}{49},$ and $p_3(P) = \frac{7}{16}.$ Therefore, the probability that the student goes through $C$ is \[p_1(C)p_2(I) + p_1(C)p_3(P) - p_1(C)p_2(I)p_3(P) = \boxed{\frac{157}{256}},\] since the events are mutually exclusive and exhaustive, and the third term is added because it was subtracted twice in the first two.

