The key to this problem is to see that $\triangle ABC$ is an equilateral triangle with side length $s=2\cdot6\cos\left(\frac{\angle P}{2}\right)$.  To prove this, drop a line segment from any vertex perpendicular to its opposite base (which by the way will be the altitude of $\triangle ABC$). The result will be two right triangles. The base of the new right triangles are each half of the base of the original triangle. The hypotenuse of the new right triangle is also the radius of the circle that circumscribes the original triangle, for one of the definition of a circle is that it is the locus of points equidistant from a given point, the given point being the center and the locus of points being the circle.  Hence, this means that the radius of a circle that circumscribes a triangle will reach every vertex of the triangle by the definition of a circle and "radius". The statement just proved why this works only for isosceles triangles, so it works for equilateral triangles as well.

Circles again will help us solve this problem because circles can be inscribed in any triangle, and they can also be circumscribed about any triangle. Similarly as how we used the definition of a circle to prove that $\triangle ABC$ was equilateral, we now use the fact that a circle can be inscribed in any triangle to help solve the problem. First, assume circle $O$ is the circle inscribed in $\triangle ABC$ and draw it out.

